Acclimation temperature affected stamina, independent of the test temperature. Indeed, irrespective of test temperature, animals were able to jump for longer when being acclimated at 24°C. However, burst performance capacity showed an interaction effect between acclimation temperature and test temperature. Indeed, animals acclimated at 24°C have their performance impacted by an acute change in test temperature. A previous study on 
 in vitro muscle performance found that isolated limb muscles in 
 X. tropicalis performed better (increase power output, shorter relaxation times) at higher temperature (up to 32°C; 
 James 
  et al., 2012
 ). Whole-animal performance in this species, however, shows somewhat lower optimal temperatures for burst performance and endurance capacity (27 and 22°C; 
 Herrel and Bonneaud 2012a). In the present study animals maintained similar burst performance capacity at both test temperatures when acclimated at 29°C. Thus, only acclimation temperatures near the optimal temperature allow animals to optimize burst performance regardless of test temperature.
